      "avalancheActivity": {
        "comment": "Over a wide area 80 to 120 cm of snow, and even more in some localities, fell on Sunday above approximately 1500 m. <br/> Strong north-easterly winds will resurface the abundant fresh snow that has fallen, forming new, large drifts. High-altitude starting zones will be replenished further. The large quantity of fresh snow as well as the wind slabs can be released easily or naturally. As a consequence of warming during the day and the solar radiation, the likelihood of avalanches being released will increase in particular on very steep sunny slopes. <br/> In addition as the day progresses at low and intermediate altitudes, numerous moist and wet avalanches are to be expected. Slides can occur on steep grassy slopes,, also on road cut slopes. <br/> The conditions are dangerous for ski touring, freeriding and snowshoe hiking.",
        "highlights": "Plenty of fresh snow, windy conditions and rising temperatures below 2,500 metres; high avalanche risk."
